 The only way to learn the program is practice, practice, practice.

54
00:04:16,720 --> 00:04:21,300
 The main topic of the course is what I think of as computational models.

55
00:04:21,939 --> 00:04:26,480
 How do we use computation to understand the world in which we live?

56
00:04:28,199 --> 00:04:29,319
 What is a model?

57
00:04:29,540 --> 00:04:35,480
 To me, I think of it as an experimental device that can help us to either understand something

58
00:04:35,480 --> 00:04:41,759
 that has happened, to sort of build a model that explains phenomena we see every day,

59
00:04:41,759 --> 00:04:47,259
 or a model that will allow us to predict the future, something that hasn't happened.

60
00:04:48,220 --> 00:04:51,279
 So you can think of, for example, a climate change model.

61
00:04:51,839 --> 00:04:57,180
 We can build models that sort of explain how the climate has changed over the millennia,

62
00:04:57,199 --> 00:05:03,160
 and then we can build probably a slightly different model that might predict what it will be like in the future.

63
00:05:03,160 --> 00:05:16,589
 So essentially what's happening is science is moving out of the wet lab and into the computer.

64
00:05:17,709 --> 00:05:21,149
 Increasingly, I'm sure you all see this, those of you who are science majors,

65
00:05:21,389 --> 00:05:26,850
 an increasing reliance on computation rather than traditional experimentation.

66
00:05:28,110 --> 00:05:33,250
 As we'll talk about, traditional experimentation is and will remain important,

67
00:05:33,250 --> 00:05:37,029
 but now it has to really be supplemented by computation.

68
00:05:38,750 --> 00:05:40,970
 We'll talk about three kinds of models,

69
00:05:41,290 --> 00:05:46,410
 optimization models, statistical models, and simulation models.

70
00:05:47,629 --> 00:05:50,449
 So let's talk first about optimization models.

71
00:05:51,930 --> 00:05:54,910
 An optimization model is a very simple thing.

72
00:05:55,470 --> 00:05:57,610
 We start with an objective function

73
00:05:58,470 --> 00:06:01,410
 that's either to be maximized or minimized.

74
00:06:02,329 --> 00:06:08,490
 For example, if I'm going from New York to Boston, I might want to find a route by car

75
00:06:08,490 --> 00:06:12,629
 or plane or train that minimizes the total travel time.

76
00:06:13,310 --> 00:06:18,629
 So my objective function would be the number of minutes spent in transit getting from A

77
00:06:18,629 --> 00:06:29,279
 to B. We then often have to layer on top of that objective function a set of constraints,

78
00:06:30,579 --> 00:06:33,000
 sometimes empty, that we have to obey.

79
00:06:33,839 --> 00:06:39,259
 So maybe the fastest way to get from New York to Boston is to take a plane,

80
00:06:39,939 --> 00:06:43,839
 but I only have $100 to spend, so that option is off the table.

81
00:06:44,560 --> 00:06:48,560
 So I have a constraint there on the amount of money I can spend.

82
00:06:49,579 --> 00:06:52,839
 Or maybe I have to be in Boston before 5 p.m.,

83
00:06:52,839 --> 00:06:57,759
 and while the bus would get me there for $15,

84
00:06:57,759 --> 00:06:59,420
 dollars, it won't get me there before 5.

85
00:06:59,860 --> 00:07:03,519
 And so maybe what I'm left with is driving,

86
00:07:04,199 --> 00:07:05,060
 something like that.

87
00:07:05,519 --> 00:07:08,819
 So objective function, something you're either minimizing

88
00:07:08,819 --> 00:07:11,660
 or maximizing, and a set of constraints

89
00:07:12,740 --> 00:07:14,740
 that eliminate some solutions.

90
00:07:16,040 --> 00:07:18,680
 And as we'll see, there's an asymmetry here.

91
00:07:18,899 --> 00:07:21,959
 We handle these two things differently.

92
00:07:26,079 --> 00:07:28,519
 We use these things all the time.

93
00:07:30,579 --> 00:07:37,139
 I commute to work using Waze, which essentially is solving, not very well I believe, an optimization

94
00:07:37,139 --> 00:07:40,600
 problem to minimize my time from home to here.

95
00:07:41,759 --> 00:07:48,879
 When you travel, maybe you log into various advisory programs that try and optimize things

96
00:07:48,879 --> 00:07:49,560
 for you.

97
00:07:50,899 --> 00:07:52,279
 They're all over the place.

98
00:07:52,279 --> 00:07:58,819
 life. Today, you really can't avoid using an optimization algorithm as you get through

99
00:07:58,819 --> 00:08:04,470
 life. All right. Pretty abstract. Let's talk about

100
00:08:04,470 --> 00:08:11,389
 a specific optimization problem called the knapsack problem. The first time I talked

101
00:08:11,389 --> 00:08:16,790
 about the knapsack problem, I neglected to show a picture of a knapsack, and I was ten

102
00:08:16,790 --> 00:08:20,610
 minutes into it before I realized most of the class had no idea what a knapsack was.

103
00:08:20,610 --> 00:08:26,689
 was. It's what we old people used to call a backpack, and they used to look more like

104
00:08:26,689 --> 00:08:36,379
 that than they look today. So the knapsack problem involves, usually it's told in terms

105
00:08:36,379 --> 00:08:43,220
 of a burglar who breaks into a house and wants to steal a bunch of stuff, but has a knapsack

106
00:08:43,220 --> 00:08:49,159
 that will only hold a finite amount of stuff that he or she wishes to steal, and so the

107
00:08:49,159 --> 00:08:52,620
 the burglar has to solve the optimization problem

108
00:08:53,240 --> 00:08:55,620
 of stealing the stuff with the most value

109
00:08:56,759 --> 00:08:59,940
 while obeying the constraint that it all

110
00:08:59,940 --> 00:09:01,240
 has to fit in the knapsack.

111
00:09:02,679 --> 00:09:05,340
 So we have an objective function.

112
00:09:07,279 --> 00:09:09,440
 I'll get the most for this when I fence it.

113
00:09:10,139 --> 00:09:12,740
 And a constraint, it has to fit in my backpack.

114
00:09:13,580 --> 00:09:17,580
 And you can guess which of these might be the most valuable

115
00:09:17,580 --> 00:09:27,960
 items here. So here's in words, written words, what I just said orally. There's

116
00:09:27,960 --> 00:09:32,159
 more stuff than you can carry and you have to choose which stuff to take and

117
00:09:32,159 --> 00:09:38,500
 which to leave behind. I should point out that there are two variants of it.

118
00:09:39,519 --> 00:09:49,080
 There's the 0-1 knapsack problem and the continuous. So the 0-1, it would be

119
00:09:49,080 --> 00:09:50,779
 illustrated by something like this.

120
00:09:51,759 --> 00:09:56,019
 So the 0, 1 knapsack problem means you either take the object or you don't.

121
00:09:56,860 --> 00:09:59,679
 I take that whole gold bar or I take none of it.

122
00:10:01,139 --> 00:10:06,179
 The continuous or so-called fractional knapsack problem says I can take pieces of it.

123
00:10:06,539 --> 00:10:12,360
 So maybe if I've taken my gold bar and shaved it into gold dust, I then can say, well, the

124
00:10:12,360 --> 00:10:15,360
 whole thing won't fit in, but I can fit in a half part of it.

125
00:10:15,360 --> 00:10:23,399
 it. The continuous knapsack problem is really boring. It's easy to solve. How do you think

126
00:10:23,399 --> 00:10:33,539
 you would solve a continuous problem? Suppose you had over here a pile of gold and a pile

127
00:10:33,539 --> 00:10:40,580
 of silver and a pile of raisins, and you wanted to maximize your value. Well, you'd fill up

128
00:10:40,580 --> 00:10:46,600
 your knapsack with gold until you either ran out of gold or ran out of space. If you haven't

129
00:10:46,600 --> 00:10:53,299
 run out of space, you'll now put silver in until you run out of space. If you still haven't

130
00:10:53,299 --> 00:10:58,059
 run out of space, well then you'll take as many raisins as you can fit in. But you can

131
00:10:58,059 --> 00:11:02,799
 solve it with what's called a greedy algorithm, and we'll talk much more about this as we

132
00:11:02,799 --> 00:11:12,919
 go forward, where you take the best thing first as long as you can, and then you move

133
00:11:12,919 --> 00:11:20,039
 on to the next thing. As we'll see, the zero-one knapsack problem is much more complicated,

134
00:11:20,720 --> 00:11:24,700
 because once you make a decision, it will affect the future decisions.

135
00:11:26,240 --> 00:11:31,259
 All right, let's look at an example. And I should probably warn you, if you're hungry,

136
00:11:31,440 --> 00:11:37,840
 this is not going to be a fun lecture. So here's my least favorite, because I always

137
00:11:37,840 --> 00:11:43,759
 want to eat more than I'm supposed to eat so the point is typically knapsack

138
00:11:43,759 --> 00:11:49,379
 problems are not physical knapsacks but some conceptual idea so let's say that

139
00:11:49,379 --> 00:11:57,399
 I'm allowed 1,500 calories of food and these are my options I have to go about

140
00:11:57,399 --> 00:12:02,480
 deciding looking at this food and it's interesting again there's things showing

141
00:12:02,480 --> 00:12:04,759
 showing up on your screen that are not showing up on my screen,

142
00:12:05,860 --> 00:12:09,100
 but they're harmless, things like how my mouse works.

143
00:12:09,759 --> 00:12:15,620
 At any rate, so I'm trying to take some fraction of this food,

144
00:12:16,519 --> 00:12:19,360
 and it can't add up to more than 1,500 calories.

145
00:12:22,779 --> 00:12:28,879
 The problem might be that once I take something that's 1,485

146
00:12:28,879 --> 00:12:33,240
 calories, I can't take anything else, or maybe 1,200 calories,

147
00:12:33,240 --> 00:12:35,279
 and everything else is more than 300.

148
00:12:35,899 --> 00:12:39,720
 So once I take one thing, it constrains possible solutions.

149
00:12:40,220 --> 00:12:42,259
 A greedy algorithm, as we'll see,

150
00:12:42,340 --> 00:12:44,539
 is not guaranteed to give me the best answer.

151
00:12:45,600 --> 00:12:46,240
 All right.

152
00:12:46,320 --> 00:12:48,159
 Let's look at a formalization of it.

153
00:12:49,120 --> 00:12:51,779
 So each item is represented by a pair,

154
00:12:53,200 --> 00:12:56,379
 the value of the item and the weight of the item.

155
00:13:00,720 --> 00:13:04,320
 And let's assume the knapsack can accommodate items

156
00:13:04,320 --> 00:13:07,340
 with a total weight of no more than w.

157
00:13:09,240 --> 00:13:11,779
 I apologize for the short variable names,

158
00:13:12,059 --> 00:13:14,440
 but they're easier to fit on a slide.

159
00:13:15,700 --> 00:13:20,200
 Finally, we're going to have a vector l of length n

160
00:13:21,019 --> 00:13:23,440
 representing the set of available items.

161
00:13:24,240 --> 00:13:27,100
 This is assuming we have n items to choose from.

162
00:13:28,899 --> 00:13:31,600
 So each element of the vector represents an item.

163
00:13:36,700 --> 00:13:38,950
 OK, so those are the items we have.

164
00:13:39,230 --> 00:13:42,990
 And then another vector, v, is going

165
00:13:42,990 --> 00:13:45,549
 to indicate whether or not an item was taken.

166
00:13:47,110 --> 00:13:49,549
 So essentially, I'm going to use a binary number

167
00:13:49,549 --> 00:13:52,850
 to represent the set of items I choose to take.

168
00:13:54,190 --> 00:13:59,929
 For item 3, say, if bit 3 is 0, I'm not taking the item.

169
00:13:59,929 --> 00:14:04,389
 If bit 3 is 1, then I am taking the item.

170
00:14:05,750 --> 00:14:10,870
 So it just shows I can now very nicely represent what I've done

171
00:14:10,870 --> 00:14:14,690
 by a single vector of 0s and 1s.

172
00:14:17,059 --> 00:14:18,580
 All right, let me pause for a second.

173
00:14:19,480 --> 00:14:22,480
 Does anyone have any questions about this setup?

174
00:14:23,039 --> 00:14:26,240
 It's important to get the setup because what we're going to see now

175
00:14:26,240 --> 00:14:30,059
 depends upon that setting in your head.

176
00:14:31,179 --> 00:14:35,279
 So I've kind of used mathematics to describe the backpack

177
00:14:35,279 --> 00:14:35,720
 problem.

178
00:14:36,120 --> 00:14:39,100
 And that's typically the way we deal with these optimization

179
00:14:39,100 --> 00:14:39,679
 problems.

180
00:14:40,120 --> 00:14:42,720
 We start with some informal description,

181
00:14:43,039 --> 00:14:46,779
 and then we translate them into a mathematical representation.

182
00:14:48,299 --> 00:14:49,500
 So here it is.

183
00:14:50,779 --> 00:14:55,399
 We're going to try and find a vector v that maximizes

184
00:14:55,399 --> 00:15:02,190
 is the sum of v sub i times i sub i.

185
00:15:05,480 --> 00:15:08,340
 Now remember, i sub i is the value of the item.

186
00:15:09,460 --> 00:15:11,820
 v sub i is either 0 or 1.

187
00:15:13,940 --> 00:15:17,779
 So if I didn't take the item, I'm

188
00:15:17,779 --> 00:15:19,340
 multiplying its value by 0.

189
00:15:19,820 --> 00:15:21,899
 So it contributes nothing to the sum.

190
00:15:22,879 --> 00:15:26,279
 If I did take the item, I'm multiplying its value by 1.

191
00:15:26,279 --> 00:15:29,480
 1, so the value of the item gets added to the sum.

192
00:15:30,779 --> 00:15:33,779
 So that tells me the value of v.

193
00:15:35,200 --> 00:15:37,779
 And I want to get the most valuable v

194
00:15:37,779 --> 00:15:40,559
 I can get, subject to the constraint

195
00:15:42,759 --> 00:15:45,860
 that if I look at the items.weight

196
00:15:46,399 --> 00:15:50,039
 and multiply it by v, the sum of the weights

197
00:15:50,039 --> 00:15:52,179
 is no greater than w.

198
00:15:54,350 --> 00:15:57,269
 So I'm playing the same trick with the values of multiplying

199
00:15:57,269 --> 00:16:03,659
 multiplying each one by 0 or 1, and that's my constraint.

200
00:16:08,100 --> 00:16:08,690
 Make sense?

201
00:16:09,169 --> 00:16:15,179
 All right, so now we have the problem formalized.

202
00:16:16,019 --> 00:16:17,639
 How do we solve it?

203
00:16:19,100 --> 00:16:22,820
 Well, the most obvious solution is brute force.

204
00:16:24,509 --> 00:16:27,840
 I enumerate all possible combinations of items

205
00:16:29,659 --> 00:16:36,980
 that are to say I generate all subsets of the items that

206
00:16:36,980 --> 00:16:37,399
 are available.

207
00:16:37,580 --> 00:16:39,179
 I don't know why it says subjects here,

208
00:16:39,759 --> 00:16:41,220
 but we should have said items.

209
00:16:41,340 --> 00:16:42,100
 Let me fix that.

210
00:16:43,960 --> 00:16:45,600
 This is called the power set.

211
00:16:46,879 --> 00:16:50,139
 So the power set of a set includes the empty subset.

212
00:16:51,120 --> 00:16:53,620
 It includes the set that includes everything

213
00:16:54,379 --> 00:16:56,919
 and everything in between.

214
00:16:56,919 --> 00:17:02,220
 between, so subsets of size 1, subsets of size 2, et cetera.

215
00:17:02,919 --> 00:17:05,859
 So now I've generated all possible sets of items.

216
00:17:07,160 --> 00:17:10,299
 I can now go through and sum up the weights

217
00:17:10,299 --> 00:17:15,000
 and remove all those sets that weigh more than I'm allowed.

218
00:17:15,799 --> 00:17:17,619
 And then from the remaining combinations,

219
00:17:18,299 --> 00:17:20,920
 choose any one whose value is the largest.

220
00:17:23,089 --> 00:17:25,170
 I say choose any one because there

221
00:17:25,170 --> 00:17:26,750
 There could be ties, in which case, I

222
00:17:26,750 --> 00:17:27,789
 don't care which I choose.

223
00:17:31,119 --> 00:17:34,619
 So it's pretty obvious that this is going

224
00:17:34,619 --> 00:17:35,920
 to give you a correct answer.

225
00:17:36,680 --> 00:17:38,500
 You're considering all possibilities

226
00:17:39,279 --> 00:17:40,380
 and choosing a winner.

227
00:17:43,519 --> 00:17:46,640
 Unfortunately, it's usually not very practical.

228
00:17:46,920 --> 00:17:51,980
 What we see here is that's what the power set is

229
00:17:51,980 --> 00:17:52,900
 if you have 100 VEC.

230
00:17:53,960 --> 00:17:55,759
 Not very practical, right?

231
00:17:55,759 --> 00:18:01,519
 right? Even for a fast computer, generating that many possibilities is going to take a

232
00:18:01,519 --> 00:18:07,599
 rather long time. So kind of disappointing. We look at it and say, well, we got a brute

233
00:18:07,599 --> 00:18:14,200
 force algorithm. It will solve the problem, but it'll take too long. We can't actually

234
00:18:14,200 --> 00:18:19,579
 do it. 100 is a pretty small number, right? We often end up solving optimization problems

235
00:18:19,579 --> 00:18:23,299
 where n is something closer to 1,000, sometimes even a million.

